Global Investors Sell Net 8.46 Billion Rupees of Indian Stocks

-- B y   P a r e s h   J a t a k i a
-- 
2011-02-11T10:55:25Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-11/global-investors-sell-net-8-46-billion-rupees-of-indian-stocks.html
Global funds sold a net 8.46 billion
rupees ($185.5 million) of Indian equities yesterday, the
nation’s market regulator said.  Foreigners purchased 30.5 billion rupees of shares and sold
38.9 billion rupees, the  Securities and Exchange Board of India 
said on its website  today . They sold a net 7.62 billion rupees
of bonds.  Global investors, attracted by  India ’s economic expansion,
bought a record 1.33 trillion rupees of shares in 2010, lifting
the benchmark index 17 percent and making it the best performer
among the world’s 10 biggest equity markets. They invested 464
billion rupees in bonds last year.  Foreign funds have placed 4.4 trillion rupees in equities
and 889.6 billion rupees in bonds since they were allowed into
the country in 1993. The previous record was in 2009 when
inflows reached 834.2 billion rupees, sparking the biggest
advance in 18 years. Funds withdrew a record 530 billion rupees
from stocks in 2008, setting off the worst annual slump.  They have sold a net 69.6 billion rupees of Indian equities
and bought 103 billion rupees of bonds so far this year.  The regulator provides data on shares bought and sold by
large investors, including trades in the primary and secondary
markets, with a delay of at least a day.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Paresh Jatakia in Mumbai at 
